---

<ProjectLayout
  title={title}
  description={description}
  keywords={keywords}
  author={authors}
  applicationName="freqtables"
  url={ogUrl}
  image={ogImage}
  imageAlt={imageAlt}
  canonical={canonicalUrl}
  robots={robots}
  lang="en"
>
  <div class="p-0 sm:p-6">
    <header class="text-center mb-8">
      <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold mb-4">ðŸ“Š freqtables</h1>
      <p class="text-lg">
        This package allows you to create simple frequency tables given a set of
        variables with their respective frequencies. This dataset can be a list,
        tuple, or a dictionary.
      </p>
    </header>

    <section class="mb-8">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-semibold mb-4">ðŸ”¹ freqtablesimple</h2>
      <p class="mb-4">
        Here are different ways to initialize <code>FreqTableSimple</code> using
        lists, dictionaries, or individual arguments:
      </p>
      <CodeBlock
        code={`import freqtable as ft

table1 = ft.FreqTableSimple([
    'A', 'A', 'A', 'B', 'B',
    'B', 'B', 'B', 'B', 'C'
])
table2 = ft.FreqTableSimple({
    'A':3, 'B':6, 'C':1
})
table3 = ft.FreqTableSimple(
    'A', 'A', 'A', 'B', 'B',
    'B', 'B', 'B', 'B', 'C'
)
table4 = ft.FreqTableSimple(
    A = 3, B = 6, C = 1
)`}
        language="python"
        client:visible
      />
      <p class="mt-4">
        Any of these initializations will result in a table similar to this:
      </p>
      <div class="text-center mt-4">
        <img
          src="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/xeland314/freqtables/refs/heads/main/examples/example0.png"
          alt="Simple Table"
          class="rounded-lg shadow-md mx-auto"
        />
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-8">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-semibold mb-4">ðŸ”¹ freqtable</h2>
      <p class="mb-4">
        It is also possible to create a frequency table with intervals using
        <code>freqtable.py</code>. For example:
      </p>
      <CodeBlock
        code={`# example1.py
import freqtable as ft

# 8 intervals are created from 0 with a width of 4:
intervals = ft.create_intervals(8, 0, 4)
frequencies = [47, 32, 25, 20, 12, 5, 4, 5]
# The table is initialized with the intervals and frequencies:
table_with_intervals = ft.FreqTable(intervals, frequencies)`}
        language="python"
        client:visible
      />
      <p class="mt-4">This will result in:</p>
      <CodeBlock
        code={`print("Table #01".center(62, "~"))
print(table_with_intervals)`}
        language="python"
        client:visible
      />
      <div class="text-center mt-4">
        <img
          src="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/xeland314/freqtables/refs/heads/main/examples/example1.png"
          alt="Table with intervals"
          class="rounded-lg shadow-md mx-auto"
        />
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-8">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-semibold mb-4">ðŸ“¦ Installation</h2>
      <p class="mb-4">
        You can clone the repository and then install the necessary
        dependencies:
      </p>
      <CodeBlock
        code={`git clone https://github.com/xeland314/freqtables`}
        client:visible
      />
      <CodeBlock code={`pip3 install -r requirements.txt`} client:visible />
      <details class="mt-4">
        <summary class="cursor-pointer text-blue-600 hover:underline">
          requirements.txt
        </summary>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-6">
          <li>tabulate &gt;= 0.8.10</li>
        </ul>
      </details>
    </section>
  </div>
</ProjectLayout>
